2026-04-26 | Detect Cycle in Grid

Question
Return true if cycle exists, else false.
	Approach
1.	Use DFS to traverse grid  
2.	For each cell:
		if not visited:
			start DFS  
3.	DFS parameters:
		current cell (x, y)  
		parent cell (px, py)  
4.	During DFS:
		for each neighbor:
			if same character:
				if not visited:
					recurse  
				else if visited and not parent:
					cycle found → return true  
5.	If no cycle found → return false  
	Time Complexity
	O(m × n)
	Space Complexity
	O(m × n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int dirs[4][2] = {{1,0},{-1,0},{0,1},{0,-1}};
    bool dfs(vector<vector<char>>& grid, int x, int y,
             int px, int py, vector<vector<bool>>& vis){
        vis[x][y] = true;
        for(auto &d : dirs){
            int nx = x + d[0];
            int ny = y + d[1];
            if(nx < 0 || ny < 0 || nx >= grid.size() || ny >= grid[0].size())
                continue;
            if(grid[nx][ny] != grid[x][y])
                continue;
            if(!vis[nx][ny]){
                if(dfs(grid, nx, ny, x, y, vis))
                    return true;
            }
            else if(nx != px || ny != py){
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
    bool containsCycle(vector<vector<char>>& grid) {
        int m = grid.size();
        int n = grid[0].size();
        vector<vector<bool>> vis(m, vector<bool>(n, false));
        for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
            for(int j = 0; j < n; j++){
                if(!vis[i][j]){
                    if(dfs(grid, i, j, -1, -1, vis))
                        return true;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
	Key Insight
This is a **cycle detection problem in an undirected graph**:
- grid cells = nodes  
- edges = adjacent same-value cells  
The trick is:
		ignore the immediate parent  
		to avoid false cycles  
This ensures correct detection of valid cycles (length ≥ 4).
